    {
      "id": "cb7e5f81c1ddb73c35887e1b1d7c083528b6be47",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2013-09-20 21:29:21.000000000",
      "message": "Change has been successfully cherry-picked as 66858bc059362504d201262202549099185e69ba",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 7
    },
    {
      "id": "5fb9ac59411d34a2dd067c058c283967f078ff4e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 284,
        "name": "Emoly Liu",
        "email": "emoly@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "liuying_emoly"
      },
      "date": "2013-09-23 13:27:18.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 7:\n\nI find this patch causes lustre-initialization-1 failure on zfs and dne-zfs test because it deleted \n/*  The device or pool/filesystem name */\nstrscpy(mop->mo_device, argv[optind], sizeof(mop->mo_device));\nfrom mkfs_lustre.c, which is a pool/filesystem name for zfs.\n\nSince mo_device in mkfs_lustre.c is used by tunefs, mkfs(ldiskfs and zfs) in the different situations for the different meanings, a simple check at the beginning is not enough. I will add this fix to the patch for LU-3991.\n\nBTW, just as Andreas mentioned, \"there will be even more cases in the future where these checks do not work (e.g. ZFS pools, or ZFS on loop, or btrfs pools, or whatever). However, I don't have a better solution to offer right now.\" Neither do I. Let's make a better fix when we have a better idea.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 7
    },
    {
      "id": "fb7c5e58928c34dbd9111cf2133bcd530fea27b8",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2013-09-24 16:27:05.000000000",
